<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="172" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,1376,1583]" pageId="21" pageNumber="172">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1376,1403]" pageId="21" pageNumber="172">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Elytra unicolored with apex rounded. Long, raised black setation of elytra often present at least in the basal area, rarely all setae light-colored; setation evidently denser in the inner two-thirds of elytra, scarce or absent in the external third. Lateral setation of abdomen “checkered”, with alternate tufts of yellow and black hairs; ventral setation black, with the exception of a whitish medial patch
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,1376,1583]" pageId="21" pageNumber="172">
Paramera (
<figureCitation box="[320,408,1521,1547]" captionStart="FIGURES 45–51" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1869,1894]" captionTargetBox="[185,1411,214,1813]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[151,1436,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 45–51. Pygopleurus scutellatus (Brullé, 1832), habitus (see also Figs. 52–54) and genitalia (see also Figs. 62–67). 45, male, common green form with strong purple shine on elytra (Laconia, Pikoulianika); 46, male, missing colored reflection on elytra (Argolis, Achladokampos); 47, female, common green form with strong purple shine on elytra (Messenia, Messini); 48, female (Corinthia, Galatas); 49, left paramere in lateral and dorsal view (Laconia, Mystras); 50, everted endophallus in left lateral view (Corinthia, Galatas); 51, left genital sclerites of female (Laconia, Polovitsa)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3458866" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3458866/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="172">Figs 49</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[419,491,1521,1548]" captionStart="FIGURES 56–67" captionStartId="24.[151,264,1910,1935]" captionTargetBox="[167,1408,181,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[164,1423,181,1885]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 56–67. Variability of paramera of Pygopleurus chrysonotus (Brullé, 1832) (56–61) and P. scutellatus (Brullé, 1832) (62–67). Left paramere in lateral and dorsal view. 56, Achaia; 57, Attika, Vravrona; 58, Central Macedonia, Koustochori; 59, Elis, Foloi; 60, Epirus, Mt. Tymfi; 61, Macedonia, Valandovo; 62, Argolis, Achladokampos; 63, Elis, Figalia; 64, Korinthia, Galatas; 65, Lakonia, Paleopanagia; 66, Messinia, Kazarma; 67, Messinia, Messini." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3458874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3458874/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="172">62–67</figureCitation>
) and everted endophallus (
<figureCitation box="[794,875,1520,1547]" captionStart="FIGURES 45–51" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1869,1894]" captionTargetBox="[185,1411,214,1813]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[151,1436,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 45–51. Pygopleurus scutellatus (Brullé, 1832), habitus (see also Figs. 52–54) and genitalia (see also Figs. 62–67). 45, male, common green form with strong purple shine on elytra (Laconia, Pikoulianika); 46, male, missing colored reflection on elytra (Argolis, Achladokampos); 47, female, common green form with strong purple shine on elytra (Messenia, Messini); 48, female (Corinthia, Galatas); 49, left paramere in lateral and dorsal view (Laconia, Mystras); 50, everted endophallus in left lateral view (Corinthia, Galatas); 51, left genital sclerites of female (Laconia, Polovitsa)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3458866" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3458866/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="172">Fig. 50</figureCitation>
) similar to those of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brulle" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[1102,1264,1521,1547]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chrysonotus">
<emphasis box="[1102,1264,1521,1547]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="172">P. chrysonotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but both diagnostic.
</paragraph>
