<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="176" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,152,359]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,524,152,179]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
Eco-ethological notes (
<figureCitation box="[423,511,152,179]" captionStart="FIGURE 55" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1940,1965]" captionTargetBox="[151,1426,1194,1915]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,1194,1915]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 55. Pygopleurus scutellatus (Brullé, 1832): geographical, altitudinal, and temporal distribution of records. Red curves showing the expected distribution if the species was uniformly present at all heights and all times (see Material and methods)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3458872" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3458872/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Fig. 55</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
The adults of this species are active for two months, between the beginning of April (
<date box="[228,323,188,215]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
8 
<superScript attach="left" box="[242,255,188,202]" fontSize="6" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">th</superScript>
April
</date>
, Korinthos and Olympia) and the beginning of June (
<date box="[932,1022,188,215]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
4 
<superScript attach="left" box="[947,960,188,202]" fontSize="6" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">th</superScript>
June
</date>
, Arkadia, Kamara, 
<quantity box="[1243,1319,188,215]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" unit="m" value="750.0">750 m</quantity>
). The alti- tudinal range is comprised from sea level (Korinthos, Olympia, Messini) to 
<quantity box="[1017,1173,225,251]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.45" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" unit="m" value="1450.0" valueMax="1600.0" valueMin="1300.0">1300–1600 m</quantity>
(Taygetos range), with records being more abundant between about 400 and 
<quantity box="[756,843,261,287]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" unit="m" value="1100.0">1100 m</quantity>
. The species is quite abundant, being often the more common 
<taxonomicName box="[259,401,297,323]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[259,401,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Pygopleurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and it is mostly found on 
<emphasis box="[721,964,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<taxonomicName box="[721,816,298,323]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Papaver" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Papaver</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[830,964,297,323]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Onopordum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Onopordum</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[1024,1198,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<taxonomicName box="[1024,1194,297,323]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cistaceae" genus="Cistus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanus">Cistus incanus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and occasionally on 
<taxonomicName box="[151,283,333,359]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ranunculaceae" genus="Ranunculus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,283,333,359]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Ranunculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and white 
<emphasis box="[407,497,333,359]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<taxonomicName authorityName="C.Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" box="[407,493,333,359]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Sinapis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Sinapis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="176" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,404,467]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,396,404,431]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Taxonomic remarks.</emphasis>
This species is very similar in appearance to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brulle" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[898,1061,405,431]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chrysonotus">
<emphasis box="[898,1061,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">P. chrysonotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from which can be distinguished by the form of paramera and everted endophallus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
